misc: Moved with his family from Rochester, NY to Washington, DC in autumn 1865.  Began the study of medicine at Georgetown Univ., but went on to Howard because that was "where the best clinical facilities were afforded."  In 1881 to '82, attended private classes of Professors Draper and Loomis at Bellevue Hosp., New York.  Was stationed at Key West, FL during the yellow fever epidemic of 1887; also served 4 years at Port Townsend, Puget Sound.  During the yellow fever epidemic of autumn 1897, was in charge of quarantine and inspection work for the state of AL.  At the beginning of the Spanish American War, was ordered to the west coast of FL to prevent the introduction of yellow fever from Cuba; among those detained at quarantine was Gen. O.O. Howard.  In 1899, organized the quarantine service in Puerto Rico, "the complete success of which was shown in the fact that for the first time in ten years, not a single case of yellow fever occurred or was introduced into the island."  Chief quarantine officer in Cuba during yellow fever epidemic at Havana, 1900 to '02.
